SIMPLE: mortify
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Mortify
<hw>Mor"ti*fy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mortified</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Mortifying</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>mortifien</ets>, F. <ets>mortifier</ets>, fr. L.
<ets>mortificare</ets>; L. <ets>mors</ets>, <ets>mortis</ets>, death +
<ets>-ficare</ets> (in comp.) to make. See <er>Mortal</er>, and
<er>-fy</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To destroy the organic texture and
vital functions of; to produce gangrene in.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To destroy the active powers or essential qualities
of; to change by chemical action.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Quicksilver is <qex>mortified</qex> with turpentine.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He <qex>mortified</qex> pearls in vinegar.</q>
<rj><qau>Hakewill.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To deaden by religious or other discipline, as the
carnal affections, bodily appetites, or worldly desires; to bring into
subjection; to abase; to humble; <as>as, to <ex>mortify</ex> the
flesh</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With fasting <qex>mortified</qex>, worn out with tears.</q>
<rj><qau>Harte.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Mortify</qex> thy learned lust.</q>
<rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Mortify</qex>, therefore, your members which are upon the
earth.</q> <rj><qau>Col. iii. 5.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To affect with vexation, chagrin; to
depress.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The news of the fatal battle of Worcester, which exceedingly
<qex>mortified</qex> our expectations.</q>
<rj><qau>Evelyn.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>How often is the ambitious man <qex>mortified</qex> with the very
praises he receives, if they do not rise so high as he thinks they
ought!</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To humiliate deeply, especially by injuring the
pride of; to embarrass painfully; to humble; <as>as, the team was
<ex>mortified</ex> to lose by 45 to 0</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> + <source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mortify</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Mortify
<hw>Mor"ti*fy</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To lose vitality
and organic structure, as flesh of a living body; to gangrene.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To practice penance from religious motives; to
deaden desires by religious discipline.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This makes him . . . give alms of all that he hath, watch, fast,
and <qex>mortify</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Law.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To be subdued; to decay, as appetites, desires,
etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mortifying</ent>⟦br⟧
